lor":null,"section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":1006216,"guid":"E5B3E1E8293F493389481CD8B85FFC43","previous_id":1006215,"previous_guid":"DE16F88D3819418DB67AD863AFACC998","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"F2470D1153CB417E938FAD80B190EF16","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":""}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"69B52AF16AC1461981F3711BA38302E4","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">Cover the opening of the bottle with its cap or aluminum foil (but do not make an air-tight seal!) and tape the bottle with autoclave tape. The autoclave tape will darken during the autoclave process if your sample has spent at least <\/div><div class = \"text-block\"> min at <\/div><div class = \"text-block\">. Use lab tape to label the bottle with your initials, the date, and the bottle contents. This will clear up any confusion later if your forget your bottle in the autoclave.<\/div><\/div>"}},{"id":1054725,"guid":"A3E638F0AD4A11E9AFBCF9329CC57F61","order_id":2,"type_id":4,"title":"duration","source":{"duration":600,"title":""}},{"id":1054726,"guid":"77E544D0AD4A11E9AFBCF9329CC57F61","order_id":3,"type_id":24,"title":"temperature","source":{"temperature":121,"unit":"\u00b0C","title":""}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":null,"section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":1006217,"guid":"71340AD8550842DEAAEB951472C151ED","previous_id":1006216,"previous_guid":"E5B3E1E8293F493389481CD8B85FFC43","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"E3146DB2E4924099988E08BD61877DA1","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":""}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"D1E49FB8896C475C951B8DCF7F3C69AC","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">Place the mixturetemperatures in the autoclave and run on a setting that gets the sample to at least <\/div><div class = \"text-block\"> under 20 psi for at least <\/div><div class = \"text-block\">. The high pressure will prevent your gel mix from boiling over at high temperatures.<\/div><\/div>"}},{"id":1054725,"guid":"AF430160AD4A11E9AFBCF9329CC57F61","order_id":2,"type_id":24,"title":"temperature","source":{"temperature":121,"unit":"\u00b0C","title":""}},{"id":1054726,"guid":"BB9155C0AD4A11E9AFBCF9329CC57F61","order_id":3,"type_id":4,"title":"duration","source":{"duration":1800,"title":""}},{"id":1054727,"guid":"102270A4FB2740D3B3A4C7FF0C42919F","order_id":4,"type_id":26,"title":"notes","source":{"id":0,"parent_id":0,"uri":"","title":"","body":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\"><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\">*Pro-Tip*<\/span><\/div><div class = \"text-block\">Although our recommended temperature should kill most potential contaminants, certain types of spores will stubbornly survive even under the harsh conditions in the autoclave. Be sure to check the literature for an appropriate sterilization technique if you are working with any weird and wonderful organisms.<\/div><\/div>","created_on":0,"changed_on":0,"creator":{"name":" ","affiliation":null,"affiliations":[],"username":"","note":null,"link":null,"image":{"source":"","placeholder":""},"badges":[],"verified":0,"is_verified_user":false,"research_interests":null,"blocked_by_you":false,"blocked_you":false,"hide_following":false},"comments":[]}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":null,"section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":1006218,"guid":"BBE5A1F0E322441C816308884354D790","previous_id":1006217,"previous_guid":"71340AD8550842DEAAEB951472C151ED","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"A0A108099BC141659D1260A545636A4A","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":""}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"9101E7C878884F538F1BC6BE054368C0","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">While your samples are sterilizing in the autoclave, you should prepare your plate pouring station:<\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><ul style = \"list-style-type:disc;\"><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\">Find an empty section of lab bench with a working flame.<\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\"><\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\">Spray down the bench with an appropriate disinfectant solution and wipe down with a paper towel.<\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\"><\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\">Count out the appropriate number of plates and stack them on your lab bench.<\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\"><\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\">Label the plates with the date and the medium they will contain including the identity of the antibiotic.<\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\"><a href=\"#\" style = \"text-decoration:underline;color:blue;cursor:pointer;\"><span style = \":;\"> <\/span><\/a><\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\"><\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\">Position the flame just to the side of where you\u2019ll be pouring your plates - be sure to leave room for your bottle of molten gel mix, a tube rack containing the appropriate antibiotics, and a section for active pouring.<\/li><\/ul><\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><ul style = \"list-style-type:disc;\"><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\">Spray down the bench with an appropriate disinfectant solution and wipe down with a paper towel.<\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\"><\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\">Count out the appropriate number of plates and stack them on your lab bench.<\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\"><\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\">Label the plates with the date and the medium they will contain including the identity of the antibiotic.<\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\"><a href=\"#\" style = \"text-decoration:underline;color:blue;cursor:pointer;\"><span style = \":;\"> <\/span><\/a><\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\"><\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\">Position the flame just to the side of where you\u2019ll be pouring your plates - be sure to leave room for your bottle of molten gel mix, a tube rack containing the appropriate antibiotics, and a section for active pouring.<\/li><\/ul><\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><ul style = \"list-style-type:disc;\"><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\">Count out the appropriate number of plates and stack them on your lab bench.<\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\"><\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\">Label the plates with the date and the medium they will contain including the identity of the antibiotic.<\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\"><a href=\"#\" style = \"text-decoration:underline;color:blue;cursor:pointer;\"><span style = \":;\"> <\/span><\/a><\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\"><\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\">Position the flame just to the side of where you\u2019ll be pouring your plates - be sure to leave room for your bottle of molten gel mix, a tube rack containing the appropriate antibiotics, and a section for active pouring.<\/li><\/ul><\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><ul style = \"list-style-type:disc;\"><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\">Label the plates with the date and the medium they will contain including the identity of the antibiotic.<\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\"><a href=\"#\" style = \"text-decoration:underline;color:blue;cursor:pointer;\"><span style = \":;\"> <\/span><\/a><\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\"><\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\">Position the flame just to the side of where you\u2019ll be pouring your plates - be sure to leave room for your bottle of molten gel mix, a tube rack containing the appropriate antibiotics, and a section for active pouring.<\/li><\/ul><\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><ul style = \"list-style-type:disc;\"><\/ul><\/div><\/div>"}},{"id":1054725,"guid":"AAFAF9E75851492DB41AE0852108D887","order_id":2,"type_id":26,"title":"notes","source":{"id":0,"parent_id":0,"uri":"","title":"","body":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\"><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\">*Pro-Tip*<\/span><\/div><div class = \"text-block\">We batch label our plates with colored marker - particular colors correspond to particular antibiotics.<\/div><\/div>","created_on":0,"changed_on":0,"creator":{"name":" ","affiliation":null,"affiliations":[],"username":"","note":null,"link":null,"image":{"source":"","placeholder":""},"badges":[],"verified":0,"is_verified_user":false,"research_interests":null,"blocked_by_you":false,"blocked_you":false,"hide_following":false},"comments":[]}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":null,"section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":1006219,"guid":"AA391489433C483E96977769B93743EF","previous_id":1006218,"previous_guid":"BBE5A1F0E322441C816308884354D790","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"EEC2A0E48C734A70B1DC13F86A86FF0F","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":""}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"2866D50277BA4D849D46BD4CAEC0CF85","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">Prepare your antibiotics. Prior to adding your antibiotic to the molten gel mix, you should create a 1000x stock solution.<\/div><\/div>"}},{"id":1054725,"guid":"BC48004B1CF7441E8B42E7BE7CAF4B71","order_id":2,"type_id":26,"title":"notes","source":{"id":0,"parent_id":0,"uri":"","title":"","body":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\"><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\">Example: <\/span><\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><span>If you\u2019ll be preparing plates with a final concentration of <\/span><a href=\"#\" style = \"text-decoration:underline;color:blue;cursor:pointer;\"><span style = \":;\"> <\/span><\/a><span> ampicillin, you should make a stock solution of <\/span><a href=\"#\" style = \"text-decoration:underline;color:blue;cursor:pointer;\"><span style = \":;\"> <\/span><\/a><span> (<\/span><a href=\"#\" style = \"text-decoration:underline;color:blue;cursor:pointer;\"><span style = \":;\"> <\/span><\/a><span>). Simply measure out <\/span><a href=\"#\" style = \"text-decoration:underline;color:blue;cursor:pointer;\"><span style = \":;\"> <\/span><\/a><span> of ampicillin powder, add it to <\/span><a href=\"#\" style = \"text-decoration:underline;color:blue;cursor:pointer;\"><span style = \":;\"> <\/span><\/a><span> of water, dissolve by vortexing, and filter sterilize.<\/span><\/div><\/div>","created_on":0,"changed_on":0,"creator":{"name":" ","affiliation":null,"affiliations":[],"username":"","note":null,"link":null,"image":{"source":"","placeholder":""},"badges":[],"verified":0,"is_verified_user":false,"research_interests":null,"blocked_by_you":false,"blocked_you":false,"hide_following":false},"comments":[]}},{"id":1054726,"guid":"A2A5B29122E845E5BDC4DF12A66F1C4A","order_id":3,"type_id":26,"title":"notes","source":{"id":0,"parent_id":0,"uri":"","title":"","body":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\"><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\">*Pro-Tip*<\/span><\/div><div class = \"text-block\">Making plates at a 2x concentration of antibiotic helps them last longer and minimizes any effects of antibiotic degradation<\/div><\/div>","created_on":0,"changed_on":0,"creator":{"name":" ","affiliation":null,"affiliations":[],"username":"","note":null,"link":null,"image":{"source":"","placeholder":""},"badges":[],"verified":0,"is_verified_user":false,"research_interests":null,"blocked_by_you":false,"blocked_you":false,"hide_following":false},"comments":[]}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":null,"section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":1006220,"guid":"700AAE21C15947D7A1E66797CE9C0889","previous_id":1006219,"previous_guid":"AA391489433C483E96977769B93743EF","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"0AC518C1E5C547DF9D4CEAD5281688E8","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":""}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"1EE5014C69044BD194A5115D05356CDA","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">(Optional) Prepare a water bath at <\/div><div class = \"text-block\"> with sufficient water to submerge ~75% of the bottle containing your molten gel mixture.<\/div><\/div>"}},{"id":1054725,"guid":"E553AFF0CE8511E98D7FE7C7D7B823F4","order_id":2,"type_id":24,"title":"temperature","source":{"temperature":60,"unit":"\u00b0C","title":""}},{"id":1054726,"guid":"7F34A04CAA90451C9996C1CB15037FDF","order_id":3,"type_id":26,"title":"notes","source":{"id":0,"parent_id":0,"uri":"","title":"","body":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\"><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\">*Pro-Tip*<\/span><\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><span>You will cool the molten agar in the water bath prior to adding the antibiotic. <\/span><a href=\"#\" style = \"text-decoration:underline;color:blue;cursor:pointer;\"><span style = \":;\"> <\/span><\/a><span> is a good temperature because the molten agar will remain liquid at this temperature but most antibiotics will not break down at this temperature. Check with your antibiotic\u2019s manufacturer to make sure this is true in your case.<\/span><\/div><\/div>","created_on":0,"changed_on":0,"creator":{"name":" ","affiliation":null,"affiliations":[],"username":"","note":null,"link":null,"image":{"source":"","placeholder":""},"badges":[],"verified":0,"is_verified_user":false,"research_interests":null,"blocked_by_you":false,"blocked_you":false,"hide_following":false},"comments":[]}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":null,"section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":1006221,"guid":"6E238B86CB0D47C49913D38A34BE052A","previous_id":1006220,"previous_guid":"700AAE21C15947D7A1E66797CE9C0889","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"34448504624042E5B84C642F465DB172","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":""}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"962393BAB7874708B56CAF9C9CCCC159","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">Retrieve your molten agar mix from the autoclave.<\/div><\/div>"}},{"id":1054725,"guid":"41B1E0A2F0194878B412C95BB81852E8","order_id":2,"type_id":26,"title":"notes","source":{"id":0,"parent_id":0,"uri":"","title":"","body":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\"><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\">*Pro-Tip*<\/span><\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><span>Once your autoclave cycle is complete, we recommend opening the door to the autoclave just a crack and leaving it open that way for ~<\/span><a href=\"#\" style = \"text-decoration:underline;color:blue;cursor:pointer;\"><span style = \":;\"> <\/span><\/a><span>. This will allow any steam to escape from the autoclave and will cool your gel-mix slightly. Even so, you should always use thermally insulated gloves when removing anything from the autoclave.<\/span><\/div><\/div>","created_on":0,"changed_on":0,"creator":{"name":" ","affiliation":null,"affiliations":[],"username":"","note":null,"link":null,"image":{"source":"","placeholder":""},"badges":[],"verified":0,"is_verified_user":false,"research_interests":null,"blocked_by_you":false,"blocked_you":false,"hide_following":false},"comments":[]}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":null,"section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":1006222,"guid":"994E3DCCC11C41F6931D171A12263B4D","previous_id":1006221,"previous_guid":"6E238B86CB0D47C49913D38A34BE052A","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"640D5B79CF6544999CECCC027F470FC9","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":""}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"48B8667119104DEF93D4EBC3BD4D2D95","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">(Optional) Partially submerge your molten gel-mix in the <\/div><div class = \"text-block\"> water bath.<\/div><\/div>"}},{"id":1054725,"guid":"7CA48520AD4B11E9AFBCF9329CC57F61","order_id":2,"type_id":24,"title":"temperature","source":{"temperature":60,"unit":"\u00b0C","title":""}},{"id":1054726,"guid":"24176499680845B8BF38473805D43447","order_id":3,"type_id":26,"title":"notes","source":{"id":0,"parent_id":0,"uri":"","title":"","body":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\"><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\">*Pro-Tip*<\/span><\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><span>You should leave the molten gel-mix in the water bath for at least <\/span><a href=\"#\" style = \"text-decoration:underline;color:blue;cursor:pointer;\"><span style = \":;\"> <\/span><\/a><span>. Do not let any of the water bath water touch the neck or top of the bottle as this water is not likely to be sterile. Cooled agar should be warm to the touch; as a rule of thumb, if you cannot take the molten agar out of the water bath wearing only lab gloves, it\u2019s not likely cool enough to add antibiotic to. To be certain your agar is at the right temperature, we recommend using a laser thermometer.<\/span><\/div><\/div>","created_on":0,"changed_on":0,"creator":{"name":" ","affiliation":null,"affiliations":[],"username":"","note":null,"link":null,"image":{"source":"","placeholder":""},"badges":[],"verified":0,"is_verified_user":false,"research_interests":null,"blocked_by_you":false,"blocked_you":false,"hide_following":false},"comments":[]}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":null,"section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":1006223,"guid":"82F228277D9943D7A4534640B5B905ED","previous_id":1006222,"previous_guid":"994E3DCCC11C41F6931D171A12263B4D","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"FBD9266CB6BE4E64AF78CCE7BF534F01","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":""}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"EFDCCB3F920340AAB5D508F6E20DF0CF","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">Light the flame at the plate pouring station and dilute your antibiotic into your ~<\/div><div class = \"text-block\"> molten gel mix using sterile technique.<\/div><\/div>"}},{"id":1054725,"guid":"8C8E01A0AD4B11E9AFBCF9329CC57F61","order_id":2,"type_id":24,"title":"temperature","source":{"temperature":60,"unit":"\u00b0C","title":""}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":null,"section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":1006224,"guid":"0269C09E30F944B5B575C9FA9C9940BF","previous_id":1006223,"previous_guid":"82F228277D9943D7A4534640B5B905ED","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"618E92151C1E43F1BD8B4A9F0CEF64B0","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":""}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"3FC96BA968B941D08883CD189D4DE098","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">Swirl the agar bottle to ensure even distribution of the antibiotic throughout the agar.<\/div><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":null,"section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":1006225,"guid":"F1547B1B2FDE4ED49DF1DC80ACA6AE0C","previous_id":1006224,"previous_guid":"0269C09E30F944B5B575C9FA9C9940BF","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"D5E3401EF62E4B0EB2A3A67B114CB20D","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":""}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"C6F0A109484B4156A4BF6F080F421560","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">Open one plate at a time next to the flame and begin pouring. Measure your desired amount of agar with a pipete for the first plate to get a good idea of what that volume looks like in your particular plate.<\/div><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":null,"section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":1006226,"guid":"61F1AB0E6187414A8C21D4516BE2A736","previous_id":1006225,"previous_guid":"F1547B1B2FDE4ED49DF1DC80ACA6AE0C","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"E5A2F8A214CE4668A32A73F9E9932A84","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":""}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"6553F214E3B14FDAB34957360E8BF79B","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">For the remainder of the plates, pour directly from the bottle.<\/div><\/div>"}},{"id":1054725,"guid":"9489593126644D7A8650A409F7AD95FF","order_id":2,"type_id":26,"title":"notes","source":{"id":0,"parent_id":0,"uri":"","title":"","body":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\"><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\">*Pro-Tips*<\/span><\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><ul style = \"list-style-type:disc;\"><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\">Be sure to swirl your plates after pouring to remove bubbles and ensure an even distrubtion of agar over the bottom of the plate. Cap each plate after pouring and stack as you pour.<\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\"><\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\">If your agar partially solidifies in the bottle while you\u2019re pouring, you should stop pouring and re-make the gel-mix. If you\u2019re making plates without any antibiotic you can alternatively re-liquefy the agar by running it through the autoclave again or by microwaving (if you microwave, beware of over-boiling!).<\/li><\/ul><\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><ul style = \"list-style-type:disc;\"><\/ul><\/div><\/div>","created_on":0,"changed_on":0,"creator":{"name":" ","affiliation":null,"affiliations":[],"username":"","note":null,"link":null,"image":{"source":"","placeholder":""},"badges":[],"verified":0,"is_verified_user":false,"research_interests":null,"blocked_by_you":false,"blocked_you":false,"hide_following":false},"comments":[]}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":null,"section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":1006227,"guid":"9294575DEB654F03B1E461A84E7C03B4","previous_id":1006226,"previous_guid":"61F1AB0E6187414A8C21D4516BE2A736","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"3F62BCE30FA14FAB9A07BB69DF7C6163","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":""}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"8FCAF83FA45B4BEFB0AFA8AC02E9682C","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">Leave your plates out on the bench to solidify.<\/div><\/div>"}},{"id":1054725,"guid":"8438CF03F5624FEFB713E6D1CE668519","order_id":2,"type_id":26,"title":"notes","source":{"id":0,"parent_id":0,"uri":"","title":"","body":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\"><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\">*Pro-Tip*<\/span><\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><span>It takes roughly <\/span><a href=\"#\" style = \"text-decoration:underline;color:blue;cursor:pointer;\"><span style = \":;\"> <\/span><\/a><span> for the plates to solidify at room temperature, however we leave them out at room temperature overnight to allow them to dry. After overnight drying, we place the plates in a plastic bag with an absorbent material to reduce condensation. The plates are then stored at <\/span><a href=\"#\" style = \"text-decoration:underline;color:blue;cursor:pointer;\"><span style = \":;\"> <\/span><\/a><span> until use.<\/span><\/div><\/div>","created_on":0,"changed_on":0,"creator":{"name":" ","affiliation":null,"affiliations":[],"username":"","note":null,"link":null,"image":{"source":"","placeholder":""},"badges":[],"verified":0,"is_verified_user":false,"research_interests":null,"blocked_by_you":false,"blocked_you":false,"hide_following":false},"comments":[]}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":null,"section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":1006228,"guid":"B19B9B005176484FBEBC75F522A5FF5B","previous_id":1006227,"previous_guid":"9294575DEB654F03B1E461A84E7C03B4","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"E1B79D3EDDCA4C02B267F288C8CC7B28","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":""}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"2AA7186699774C5D81010D87485ECAAF","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">(Optional) Once your plates have solidified and dried, you should test them to make sure the antibiotic functions properly:<\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><ul style = \"list-style-type:disc;\"><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\">Take out two plates.<\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\"><\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\">On the first plate, streak out a strain that you know to be resistant to the antibiotic.<\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\"><\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\">On the second plate, streak out a strain that\u2019s not resistant to the antibiotic.<\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\"><\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\">Incubate both plates overnight at the appropriate growth temperature and check for growth. See our sample data section below for positive and negative test results.<\/li><\/ul><\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><ul style = \"list-style-type:disc;\"><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\">On the first plate, streak out a strain that you know to be resistant to the antibiotic.<\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\"><\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\">On the second plate, streak out a strain that\u2019s not resistant to the antibiotic.<\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\"><\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\">Incubate both plates overnight at the appropriate growth temperature and check for growth. See our sample data section below for positive and negative test results.<\/li><\/ul><\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><ul style = \"list-style-type:disc;\"><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\">On the second plate, streak out a strain that\u2019s not resistant to the antibiotic.<\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\"><\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\">Incubate both plates overnight at the appropriate growth temperature and check for growth. See our sample data section below for positive and negative test results.<\/li><\/ul><\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><ul style = \"list-style-type:disc;\"><\/ul><\/div><\/div>"}},{"id":1054725,"guid":"DEE73D3600F5494F8194AF64CC03D252","order_id":2,"type_id":26,"title":"notes","source":{"id":0,"parent_id":0,"uri":"","title":"","body":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\"><h2><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\">Sample Data<\/span><\/h2><\/div><div class = \"text-block\">In all cases below (-) indicates that the tested strain is not supposed to be resistant to the antibiotic, (+) indicates that the tested strain is supposed to be resistant to the antibiotic.<\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\">Positive Result: Only the Resistant Strain Grows <\/span><\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><span>If everything was prepared properly, you should see growth of only the resistant strain. If you get this final result, your plates are ready for use or storage at <\/span><a href=\"#\" style = \"text-decoration:underline;color:blue;cursor:pointer;\"><span style = \":;\"> <\/span><\/a><span>. You should not store your plates for longer than 1 month at any temperature and should always check for contamination prior to use.<\/span><\/div><div style = \"text-align :; float : ;\"><img style = \"\" src = \"https:\/\/media.addgene.org\/data\/easy-thumbnails\/filer_public\/cms\/filer_public\/22\/cd\/22cda35a-6068-4bff-9aba-38d230d67975\/postiveresult_tjf_2016_9_14-01-01.png__400x228_q85_subsampling-2_upscale.png\" \/><\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\">Negative Result 1: Both Strains Grow <\/span><\/div><div class = \"text-block\">Assuming the appropriate strains were streaked on the appropriate plates, then if both strains grow, it\u2019s possible that: <\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><ol style = \"list-style-type: decimal;\"><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;\">The antibiotic broke down. <\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;\">You forgot to add the antibiotic. <\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;\">You added the antibiotic at too low a concentration for selection.<\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;\"><a href=\"#\" style = \"text-decoration:underline;color:blue;cursor:pointer;\"><span style = \":;\"> <\/span><\/a><\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;\"><\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;\"><\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;\"><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\">Negative Result 2: Neither Strains Grows <\/span><\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;\">If neither strain grows, it's possible that: <\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;\">You used the wrong antibiotic. <\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;\">Your antibiotic is at too high a concentration. <\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;\">One or both of your strains are no longer viable.You can check for this possibility by streaking out both strains on plates without any antibiotic.<\/li><\/ol><\/div><div style = \"text-align :; float : ;\"><img style = \"\" src = \"https:\/\/media.addgene.org\/data\/easy-thumbnails\/filer_public\/cms\/filer_public\/95\/2c\/952c41ab-9b93-4eaa-94bc-faa0d6b51f54\/bothstrainsgrow_tjf_9_14_2016-01.png__400x228_q85_subsampling-2_upscale.png\" \/><\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\">Negative Result 2: Neither Strains Grows <\/span><\/div><div class = \"text-block\">If neither strain grows, it's possible that: <\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><ol style = \"list-style-type: decimal;\"><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;\">You used the wrong antibiotic. <\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;\">Your antibiotic is at too high a concentration. <\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;\">One or both of your strains are no longer viable.You can check for this possibility by streaking out both strains on plates without any antibiotic.<\/li><\/ol><\/div><div style = \"text-align :; float : ;\"><img style = \"\" src = \"https:\/\/media.addgene.org\/data\/easy-thumbnails\/filer_public\/cms\/filer_public\/a9\/8d\/a98d283a-6e13-46c8-982f-0605d4d9f89b\/neitherstrainggrows_tjf_2016_9_14-01.png__400x228_q85_subsampling-2_upscale.png\" \/><\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\">Negative Result 3: Only the Non-resistant Strain Grows <\/span><\/div><div class = \"text-block\">If only the non-resistant strain grows, it\u2019s likely that you\u2019ve used the wrong antibiotic, or confused your strains.<\/div><div style = \"text-align :; float : ;\"><img style = \"\" src = \"https:\/\/media.addgene.org\/data\/easy-thumbnails\/filer_public\/cms\/filer_public\/61\/e7\/61e72140-3820-40b3-a2f2-4910b0db3435\/nonresistantstraingrows_tjf_9_14_2016-01.png__400x228_q85_subsampling-2_upscale.png\" \/><\/div><\/div>","created_on":0,"changed_on":0,"creator":{"name":" ","affiliation":null,"affiliations":[],"username":"","note":null,"link":null,"image":{"source":"","placeholder":""},"badges":[],"verified":0,"is_verified_user":false,"research_interests":null,"blocked_by_you":false,"blocked_you":false,"hide_following":false},"comments":[]}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":null,"section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0}],"document":null,"materials":[],"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\"><span>The following protocol is for making LB agar plates for the purpose of bacterial selection (500mL of LB agar makes about 25 LB agar plates). For the full abstract and additional resources, please visit <\/span><a href=\"https:\/\/www.addgene.org\/plasmid_protocols\/bacterial_plates\" style = \"text-decoration:underline;color:blue;cursor:pointer;\"><span style = \":;\">https:\/\/www.addgene.org\/plasmid_protocols\/bacterial_plates\/<\/span><\/a><\/div><\/div>","changed_on":1597962559}